00043 class OrderedDict(dict):
00044     'Dictionary that remembers insertion order'
00045     # An inherited dict maps keys to values.
00046     # The inherited dict provides __getitem__, __len__, __contains__, and get.
00047     # The remaining methods are order-aware.
00048     # Big-O running times for all methods are the same as for regular dictionaries.
00049 
00050     # The internal self.__map dictionary maps keys to links in a doubly linked list.
00051     # The circular doubly linked list starts and ends with a sentinel element.
00052     # The sentinel element never gets deleted (this simplifies the algorithm).
00053     # Each link is stored as a list of length three:  [PREV, NEXT, KEY].
00054 
00055     def __init__(self, *args, **kwds):
00056         '''Initialize an ordered dictionary.  Signature is the same as for
00057         regular dictionaries, but keyword arguments are not recommended
00058         because their insertion order is arbitrary.
00059 
00060         '''
00061         if len(args) > 1:
00062             raise TypeError('expected at most 1 arguments, got %d' % len(args))
00063         try:
00064             self.__root
00065         except AttributeError:
00066             self.__root = root = []                     # sentinel node
00067             root[:] = [root, root, None]
00068             self.__map = {}
00069         self.__update(*args, **kwds)
00070 
00071     def __setitem__(self, key, value, dict_setitem=dict.__setitem__):
00072         'od.__setitem__(i, y) <==> od[i]=y'
00073         # Setting a new item creates a new link which goes at the end of the linked
00074         # list, and the inherited dictionary is updated with the new key/value pair.
00075         if key not in self:
00076             root = self.__root
00077             last = root[0]
00078             last[1] = root[0] = self.__map[key] = [last, root, key]
00079         dict_setitem(self, key, value)
00080 
00081     def __delitem__(self, key, dict_delitem=dict.__delitem__):
00082         'od.__delitem__(y) <==> del od[y]'
00083         # Deleting an existing item uses self.__map to find the link which is
00084         # then removed by updating the links in the predecessor and successor nodes.
00085         dict_delitem(self, key)
00086         link_prev, link_next, key = self.__map.pop(key)
00087         link_prev[1] = link_next
00088         link_next[0] = link_prev
00089 
00090     def __iter__(self):
00091         'od.__iter__() <==> iter(od)'
00092         root = self.__root
00093         curr = root[1]
00094         while curr is not root:
00095             yield curr[2]
00096             curr = curr[1]
00097 
00098     def __reversed__(self):
00099         'od.__reversed__() <==> reversed(od)'
00100         root = self.__root
00101         curr = root[0]
00102         while curr is not root:
00103             yield curr[2]
00104             curr = curr[0]
00105 
00106     def clear(self):
00107         'od.clear() -> None.  Remove all items from od.'
00108         try:
00109             for node in self.__map.itervalues():
00110                 del node[:]
00111             root = self.__root
00112             root[:] = [root, root, None]
00113             self.__map.clear()
00114         except AttributeError:
00115             pass
00116         dict.clear(self)
00117 
00118     def popitem(self, last=True):
00119         '''od.popitem() -> (k, v), return and remove a (key, value) pair.
00120         Pairs are returned in LIFO order if last is true or FIFO order if false.
00121 
00122         '''
00123         if not self:
00124             raise KeyError('dictionary is empty')
00125         root = self.__root
00126         if last:
00127             link = root[0]
00128             link_prev = link[0]
00129             link_prev[1] = root
00130             root[0] = link_prev
00131         else:
00132             link = root[1]
00133             link_next = link[1]
00134             root[1] = link_next
00135             link_next[0] = root
00136         key = link[2]
00137         del self.__map[key]
00138         value = dict.pop(self, key)
00139         return key, value

00169     # Suppress 'OrderedDict.update: Method has no argument':
00170     # pylint: disable=E0211
00171     def update(*args, **kwds):
00172         '''od.update(E, **F) -> None.  Update od from dict/iterable E and F.
00173 
00174         If E is a dict instance, does:           for k in E: od[k] = E[k]
00175         If E has a .keys() method, does:         for k in E.keys(): od[k] = E[k]
00176         Or if E is an iterable of items, does:   for k, v in E: od[k] = v
00177         In either case, this is followed by:     for k, v in F.items(): od[k] = v
00178 
00179         '''
00180         if len(args) > 2:
00181             raise TypeError('update() takes at most 2 positional '
00182                             'arguments (%d given)' % (len(args),))
00183         elif not args:
00184             raise TypeError('update() takes at least 1 argument (0 given)')
00185         self = args[0]
00186         # Make progressively weaker assumptions about "other"
00187         other = ()
00188         if len(args) == 2:
00189             other = args[1]
00190         if isinstance(other, dict):
00191             for key in other:
00192                 self[key] = other[key]
00193         elif hasattr(other, 'keys'):
00194             for key in other.keys():
00195                 self[key] = other[key]
00196         else:
00197             for key, value in other:
00198                 self[key] = value
00199         for key, value in kwds.items():
00200             self[key] = value

00206     def pop(self, key, default=__marker):
00207         '''od.pop(k[,d]) -> v, remove specified key and return the corresponding value.
00208         If key is not found, d is returned if given, otherwise KeyError is raised.
00209 
00210         '''
00211         if key in self:
00212             result = self[key]
00213             del self[key]
00214             return result
00215         if default is self.__marker:
00216             raise KeyError(key)
00217         return default

00219     def setdefault(self, key, default=None):
00220         'od.setdefault(k[,d]) -> od.get(k,d), also set od[k]=d if k not in od'
00221         if key in self:
00222             return self[key]
00223         self[key] = default
00224         return default

00226     def __repr__(self, _repr_running={}):
00227         'od.__repr__() <==> repr(od)'
00228         call_key = id(self), _get_ident()
00229         if call_key in _repr_running:
00230             return '...'
00231         _repr_running[call_key] = 1
00232         try:
00233             if not self:
00234                 return '%s()' % (self.__class__.__name__,)
00235             return '%s(%r)' % (self.__class__.__name__, self.items())
00236         finally:
00237             del _repr_running[call_key]

00239     def __reduce__(self):
00240         'Return state information for pickling'
00241         items = [[k, self[k]] for k in self]
00242         inst_dict = vars(self).copy()
00243         for k in vars(OrderedDict()):
00244             inst_dict.pop(k, None)
00245         if inst_dict:
00246             return (self.__class__, (items,), inst_dict)
00247         return self.__class__, (items,)

00253     @classmethod
00254     def fromkeys(cls, iterable, value=None):
00255         '''OD.fromkeys(S[, v]) -> New ordered dictionary with keys from S
00256         and values equal to v (which defaults to None).
00257 
00258         '''
00259         d = cls()
00260         for key in iterable:
00261             d[key] = value
00262         return d

00264     def __eq__(self, other):
00265         '''od.__eq__(y) <==> od==y.  Comparison to another OD is order-sensitive
00266         while comparison to a regular mapping is order-insensitive.
00267 
00268         '''
00269         if isinstance(other, OrderedDict):
00270             return len(self)==len(other) and self.items() == other.items()
00271         return dict.__eq__(self, other)
